@c    THE BOOK OF NEHEMIAS, WHICH IS CALLED THE SECOND OF ESDRAS



@c    This Book takes its name from the writer, who was cupbearer to
@c    Artaxerxes (surnamed Longimanus) king of Persia, and was sent by him
@c    with a commission to rebuild the walls of Jerusalem.  It is also called
@c    the second book of Esdras; because it is a continuation of the history,
@c    begun by Esdras, of the state of the people of God after their return
@c    from captivity.



@c    2 Esdras Chapter 1


@c    Nehemias hearing the miserable state of his countrymen in Judea,
@c    lamenteth, fasteth, and prayeth to God for their relief.

@c    1:1. The words of Nehemias the son of Helchias.  And it came to pass in
@c    the month of Casleu, in the twentieth year, as I was in the castle of
@c    Susa,

@c    1:2. That Hanani one of my brethren came, he and some men of Juda; and
@c    I asked them concerning the Jews, that remained and were left of the
@c    captivity, and concerning Jerusalem.

@c    1:3. And they said to me:  They that have remained, and are left of the
@c    captivity there in the province, are in great affliction, and reproach:
@c    and the wall of Jerusalem is broken down, and the gates thereof are
@c    burnt with fire.

@c    1:4. And when I had heard these words, I sat down, and wept, and
@c    mourned for many days:  and I fasted, and prayed before the face of the
@c    God of heaven.

@c    1:5. And I said:  I beseech thee, O Lord God of heaven, strong, great,
@c    and terrible, who keepest covenant and mercy with those that love thee,
@c    and keep thy commandments:

@c    1:6. Let thy ears be attentive, and thy eyes open, to hear the prayer
@c    of thy servant, which I pray before thee now, night and day, for the
@c    children of Israel thy servants:  and I confess the sins of the children
@c    of Israel, by which they have sinned against thee:  I and my father's
@c    house have sinned.

@c    1:7. We have been seduced by vanity, and have not kept thy
@c    commandments, and ceremonies and judgments, which thou hast commanded
@c    thy servant Moses.

@c    1:8. Remember the word that thou commandedst to Moses thy servant,
@c    saying:  If you shall transgress, I will scatter you abroad among the
@c    nations:

@c    1:9. But if you return to me, and keep my commandments, and do them,
@c    though you should be led away to the uttermost parts of the world, I
@c    will gather you from thence, and bring you back to the place which I
@c    have chosen for my name to dwell there.

@c    1:10. And these are thy servants, and thy people:  whom thou hast
@c    redeemed by thy great strength, and by thy mighty hand.

@c    1:11. I beseech thee, O Lord, let thy ear be attentive to the prayer of
@c    thy servant, and to the prayer of thy servants who desire to fear thy
@c    name:  and direct thy servant this day, and give him mercy before this
@c    man.  For I was the king's cupbearer.



@c    2 Esdras Chapter 2


@c    Nehemias with commission from king Artaxerxes cometh to Jerusalem:  and
@c    exhorteth the Jews to rebuild the walls.

@c    2:1. And it came to pass in the month of Nisan, in the twentieth year
@c    of Artaxerxes the king:  that wine was before him, and I took up the
@c    wine, and gave it to the king:  and I was as one languishing away before
@c    his face.

@c    2:2. And the king said to me:  Why is thy countenance sad, seeing thou
@c    dost not appear to be sick?  this is not without cause, but some evil, I
@c    know not what, is in thy heart.  And I was seized with an exceeding
@c    great fear:

@c    2:3. And I said to the king:  O king, live for ever:  why should not my
@c    countenance be sorrowful, seeing the city of the place of the
@c    sepulchres of my fathers is desolate, and the gates thereof are burnt
@c    with fire?

@c    2:4. Then the king said to me:  For what dost thou make request?  And I
@c    prayed to the God of heaven,

@c    2:5. And I said to the king:  If it seem good to the king, and if thy
@c    servant hath found favour in thy sight, that thou wouldst send me into
@c    Judea to the city of the sepulchre of my father, and I will build it.

@c    2:6. And the king said to me, and the queen that sat by him:  For how
@c    long shall thy journey be, and when wilt thou return?  And it pleased
@c    the king, and he sent me:  and I fixed him a time.

@c    2:7. And I said to the king:  If it seem good to the king, let him give
@c    me letters to the governors of the country beyond the river, that they
@c    convey me over, till I come into Judea:

@c    2:8. And a letter to Asaph the keeper of the king's forest, to give me
@c    timber that I may cover the gates of the tower of the house, and the
@c    walls of the city, and the house that I shall enter into.  And the king
@c    gave me according to the good hand of my God with me.

@c    2:9. And I came to the governors of the country beyond the river, and
@c    gave them the king's letters.  And the king had sent with me captains of
@c    soldiers, and horsemen.

@c    2:10. And Sanaballat the Horonite, and Tobias the servant, the
@c    Ammonite, heard it, and it grieved them exceedingly, that a man was
@c    come, who sought the prosperity of the children of Israel.

@c    2:11. And I came to Jerusalem, and was there three days.

@c    2:12. And I arose in the night, I and some few men with me, and I told
@c    not any man what God had put in my heart to do in Jerusalem, and there
@c    was no beast with me, but the beast that I rode upon.

@c    2:13. And I went out by night by the gate of the valley, and before the
@c    dragon fountain, and to the dung gate, and I viewed the wall of
@c    Jerusalem which was broken down, and the gates thereof which were
@c    consumed with fire.

@c    2:14. And I passed to the gate of the fountain, and to the king's
@c    aqueduct, and there was no place for the beast on which I rode to pass.

@c    2:15. And I went up in the night by the torrent, and viewed the wall,
@c    and going back I came to the gate of the valley, and returned.

@c    2:16. But the magistrates knew not whither I went, or what I did:
@c    neither had I as yet told any thing to the Jews, or to the priests, or
@c    to the nobles, or to the magistrates, or to the rest that did the work.

@c    2:17. Then I said to them:  You know the affliction wherein we are,
@c    because Jerusalem is desolate, and the gates thereof are consumed with
@c    fire:  come, and let us build up the walls of Jerusalem, and let us be
@c    no longer a reproach.

@c    2:18. And I shewed them how the hand of my God was good with me, and
@c    the king's words, which he had spoken to me, and I said:  Let us rise
@c    up, and build.  And their hands were strengthened in good.

@c    2:19. But Sanaballat the Horonite, and Tobias the servant, the
@c    Ammonite, and Gossem the Arabian heard of it, and they scoffed at us,
@c    and despised us, and said:  What is this thing that you do?  are you
@c    going to rebel against the king?

@c    2:20. And I answered them, and said to them:  The God of heaven he
@c    helpeth us, and we are his servants:  let us rise up and build:  but you
@c    have no part, nor justice, nor remembrance in Jerusalem.



@c    2 Esdras Chapter 3


@c    They begin to build the walls:  the names and order of the builders.

@c    3:1. Then Eliasib the high priest arose, and his brethren the priests,
@c    and they built the flock gate:  they sanctified it, and set up the doors
@c    thereof, even unto the tower of a hundred cubits they sanctified it
@c    unto the tower of Hananeel.

@c    3:2. And next to him the men of Jericho built:  and next to them built
@c    Zachur the son of Amri.

@c    3:3. But the fish gate the sons of Asnaa built:  they covered it, and
@c    set up the doors thereof, and the locks, and the bars.  And next to them
@c    built Marimuth the son of Urias the son of Accus.

@c    4. And next to him built Mosollam the son of Barachias, the son of
@c    Merezebel, and next to them built Sadoc the son of Baana.

@c    5. And next to them the Thecuites built:  but their great men did not
@c    put their necks to the work of their Lord.

@c    3:6. And Joiada the son of Phasea, and Mosollam the son of Besodia
@c    built the old gate:  they covered it and set up the doors thereof, and
@c    the locks, and the bars.

@c    3:7. And next to them built Meltias the Gabaonite, and Jadon the
@c    Meronathite, the men of Gabaon and Maspha, for the governor that was in
@c    the country beyond the river.

@c    3:8. And next to him built Eziel the son of Araia the goldsmith:  and
@c    next to him built Ananias the son of the perfumer:  and they left
@c    Jerusalem unto the wall of the broad street.

@c    3:9. And next to him built Raphaia the son of Hur, lord of the street
@c    of Jerusalem.

@c    3:10. And next to him Jedaia the son of Haromaph over against his own
@c    house:  and next to him built Hattus the son of Hasebonia.

@c    3:11. Melchias the son of Herem, and Hasub the son of Phahath Moab,
@c    built half the street, and the tower of the furnaces.

@c    3:12. And next to him built Sellum the son of Alohes, lord of half the
@c    street of Jerusalem, he and his daughters.

@c    3:13. And the gate of the valley Hanun built, and the inhabitants of
@c    Zanoe:  they built it, and set up the doors thereof, and the locks, and
@c    the bars, and a thousand cubits in the wall unto the gate of the
@c    dunghill.

@c    3:14. And the gate of the dunghill Melchias the son of Rechab built,
@c    lord of the street of Bethacharam:  he built it, and set up the doors
@c    thereof, and the locks, and the bars.

@c    3:15. And the gate of the fountain, Sellum, the son of Cholhoza, built,
@c    lord of the street of Maspha:  he built it, and covered it, and set up
@c    the doors thereof, and the locks, and the bars, and the walls of the
@c    pool of Siloe unto the king's guard, and unto the steps that go down
@c    from the city of David.

@c    3:16. After him built Nehemias the son of Azboc, lord of half the
@c    street of Bethsur, as far as over against the sepulchre of David, and
@c    to the pool, that was built with great labour, and to the house of the
@c    mighty.

@c    3:17. After him built the Levites, Rehum the son of Benni.  After him
@c    built Hasebias, lord of half the street of Ceila in his own street.

@c    3:18. After him built their brethren Bavai the son of Enadad, lord of
@c    half Ceila.

@c    3:19. And next to him Aser the son of Josue, lord of Maspha, built
@c    another measure, over against the going up of the strong corner.

@c    3:20. After him in the mount Baruch the son of Zachai built another
@c    measure, from the corner to the door of the house of Eliasib the high
@c    priest.

@c    3:21. After him Merimuth the son of Urias the son of Haccus, built
@c    another measure, from the door of the house of Eliasib, to the end of
@c    the house of Eliasib.

@c    3:22. And after him built the priests, the men of the plains of the
@c    Jordan.

@c    3:23. After him built Benjamin and Hasub, over against their own house:
@c    and after him built Azarias the son of Maasias the son of Ananias over
@c    against his house.

@c    3:24. After him built Bennui the son of Hanadad another measure, from
@c    the house of Azarias unto the bending, and unto the corner.

@c    3:25. Phalel, the son of Ozi, over against the bending and the tower,
@c    which lieth out from the king's high house, that is, in the court of
@c    the prison:  after him Phadaia the son of Pharos.

@c    3:26. And the Nathinites dwelt in Ophel, as far as over against the
@c    water gate toward the east, and the tower that stood out.

@c    3:27. After him the Thecuites built another measure over against, from
@c    the great tower that standeth out unto the wall of the temple.

@c    3:28. And upward from the horse gate the priests built, every man over
@c    against his house.

@c    3:29. After them built Sadoc the son of Emmer over against his house.
@c    And after him built Semaia the son of Sechenias, keeper of the east
@c    gate.

@c    3:30. After him built Hanania the son of Selemia, and Hanun the sixth
@c    son of Seleph, another measure:  after him built Mosollam the son of
@c    Barachias over against his treasury.  After him Melcias the goldsmith's
@c    son built unto the house of the Nathinites, and of the sellers of small
@c    wares, over against the judgment gate, and unto the chamber of the
@c    corner.

@c    3:31. And within the chamber of the corner of the flock gate, the
@c    goldsmiths and the merchants built.



@c    2 Esdras Chapter 4


@c    The building is carried on notwithstanding the opposition of their
@c    enemies.

@c    4:1. And it came to pass, that when Sanaballat heard that we were
@c    building the wall he was angry:  and being moved exceedingly he scoffed
@c    at the Jews.

@c    4:2. And said before his brethren, and the multitude of the Samaritans:
@c    What are the silly Jews doing?  Will the Gentiles let them alone?  will
@c    they sacrifice and make an end in a day?  are they able to raise stones
@c    out of the heaps of the rubbish, which are burnt?

@c    4:3. Tobias also the Ammonite who was by him said:  Let them build:  if a
@c    fox go up, he will leap over their stone wall.

@c    4:4. Hear thou our God, for we are despised:  turn their reproach upon
@c    their own head, and give them to be despised in a land of captivity.

@c    4:5. Cover not their iniquity, and let not their sin be blotted out
@c    from before thy face, because they have mocked thy builders.

@c    4:6. So we built the wall, and joined it all together unto the half
@c    thereof:  and the heart of the people was excited to work.

@c    4:7. And it came to pass, when Sanaballat, and Tobias, and the
@c    Arabians, and the Ammonites, and the Azotians heard that the walls of
@c    Jerusalem were made up, and the breaches began to be closed, that they
@c    were exceedingly angry.

@c    4:8. And they all assembled themselves together, to come, and to fight
@c    against Jerusalem, and to prepare ambushes.

@c    4:9. And we prayed to our God, and set watchmen upon the wall day and
@c    night against them.

@c    4:10. And Juda said:  The strength of the bearer of burdens is decayed,
@c    and the rubbish is very much, and we shall not be able to build the
@c    wall.

@c    4:11. And our enemies said:  Let them not know, nor understand, till we
@c    come in the midst of them, and kill them, and cause the work to cease.

@c    4:12. And it came to pass, that when the Jews that dwelt by them came
@c    and told us ten times, out of all the places from whence they came to
@c    us,

@c    4:13. I set the people in the place behind the wall round about in
@c    order, with their swords, and spears, and bows.

@c    4:14. And I looked and rose up:  and I said to the chief men and the
@c    magistrates, and to the rest of the common people:  be not afraid of
@c    them.  Remember the Lord who is great and terrible, and fight for your
@c    brethren, your sons, and your daughters, and your wives, and your
@c    houses.

@c    4:15. And it came to pass, when our enemies heard that the thing had
@c    been told us, that God defeated their counsel.  And we returned all of
@c    us to the walls, every man to his work.

@c    4:16. And it came to pass from that day forward, that half of their
@c    young men did the work, and half were ready for to fight, with spears,
@c    and shields, and bows, and coats of mail, and the rulers were behind
@c    them in all the house of Juda.

@c    4:17. Of them that built on the wall and that carried burdens, and that
@c    laded:  with one of his hands he did the work, and with the other he
@c    held a sword.

@c    4:18. For every one of the builders was girded with a sword about his
@c    reins.  And they built, and sounded with a trumpet by me.

@c    4:19. And I said to the nobles, and to the magistrates, and to the rest
@c    of the common people:  The work is great and wide, and we are separated
@c    on the wall one far from another:

@c    4:20. In what place soever you shall hear the sound of the trumpet, run
@c    all thither unto us:  our God will fight for us.

@c    4:21. And let us do the work:  and let one half of us hold our spears
@c    from the rising of the morning, till the stars appear.

@c    4:22. At that time also I said to the people:  Let every one with his
@c    servant stay in the midst of Jerusalem, and let us take our turns in
@c    the night, and by day, to work.

@c    4:23. Now I and my brethren, and my servants, and the watchmen that
@c    followed me, did not put off our clothes:  only every man stripped
@c    himself when he was to be washed.



@c    2 Esdras Chapter 5


@c    Nehemias blameth the rich, for their oppressing the poor.  His
@c    exhortation, and bounty to his countrymen.

@c    5:1. Now there was a great cry of the people, and of their wives
@c    against their brethren the Jews.

@c    5:2. And there were some that said:  Our sons and our daughters are very
@c    many:  let us take up corn for the price of them, and let us eat and
@c    live.

@c    5:3. And there were some that said:  Let us mortgage our lands, and our
@c    vineyards, and our houses, and let us take corn because of the famine.

@c    5:4. And others said:  Let us borrow money for the king's tribute, and
@c    let us give up our fields and vineyards:

@c    5:5. And now our flesh is as the flesh of our brethren:  and our
@c    children as their children.  Behold we bring into bondage our sons and
@c    our daughters, and some of our daughters are bondwomen already, neither
@c    have we wherewith to redeem them, and our fields and our vineyards
@c    other men possess.

@c    5:6. And I was exceedingly angry when I heard their cry according to
@c    these words.

@c    5:7. And my heart thought with myself:  and I rebuked the nobles and
@c    magistrates, and said to them:  Do you every one exact usury of your
@c    brethren?  And I gathered together a great assembly against them,

@c    5:8. And I said to them:  We, as you know, have redeemed according to
@c    our ability our brethren the Jews, that were sold to the Gentiles:  and
@c    will you then sell your brethren, for us to redeem them?  And they held
@c    their peace, and found not what to answer.

@c    5:9. And I said to them:  The thing you do is not good:  why walk you not
@c    in the fear of our God, that we be not exposed to the reproaches of the
@c    Gentiles our enemies?

@c    5:10. Both I and my brethren, and my servants, have lent money and corn
@c    to many:  let us all agree not to call for it again; let us forgive the
@c    debt that is owing to us.

@c    5:11. Restore ye to them this day their fields, and their vineyards,
@c    and their oliveyards, and their houses:  and the hundredth part of the
@c    money, and of the corn, the wine, and the oil, which you were wont to
@c    exact of them, give it rather for them.

@c    5:12. And they said:  We will restore, and we will require nothing of
@c    them:  and we will do as thou sayest.  And I called the priests and took
@c    an oath of them, to do according to what I had said.

@c    5:13. Moreover I shook my lap, and said:  So may God shake every man
@c    that shall not accomplish this word, out of his house, and out of his
@c    labours, thus may he be shaken out, and become empty.  And all the
@c    multitude said:  Amen.  And they praised God.  And the people did
@c    according to what was said.

@c    5:14. And from the day, in which the king commanded me to be governor
@c    in the land of Juda, from the twentieth year even to the two and
@c    thirtieth year of Artaxerxes the king, for twelve years, I and my
@c    brethren did not eat the yearly allowance that was due to the
@c    governors.

@c    5:15. But the former governors that had been before me, were chargeable
@c    to the people, and took of them in bread, and wine, and in money every
@c    day forty sicles:  and their officers also oppressed the people.  But I
@c    did not so for the fear of God.

@c    5:16. Moreover I built in the work of the wall, and I bought no land,
@c    and all my servants were gathered together to the work.

@c    5:17. The Jews also and the magistrates to the number of one hundred
@c    and fifty men, were at my table, besides them that came to us from
@c    among the nations that were round about us.

@c    5:18. And there was prepared for me day be day one ox, and six choice
@c    rams, besides fowls, and once in ten days I gave store of divers wines,
@c    and many other things:  yet I did not require my yearly allowance as
@c    governor:  for the people were very much impoverished.

@c    5:19. Remember me, O my God, for good according to all that I have done
@c    for this people.



@c    2 Esdras Chapter 6


@c    The enemies seek to terrify Nehemias.  He proceedeth and finisheth the
@c    wall.

@c    6:1. And it came to pass, when Sanaballat, and Tobias, and Gossem the
@c    Arabian, and the rest of our enemies, heard that I had built the wall,
@c    and that there was no breach left in it, (though at that time I had not
@c    set up the doors in the gates,)

@c    6:2. Sanaballat and Gossem sent to me, saying:  Come, and let us make a
@c    league together in the villages, in the plain of Ono.  But they thought
@c    to do me mischief.

@c    6:3. And I sent messengers to them, saying:  I am doing a great work,
@c    and I cannot come down, lest it be neglected whilst I come, and go down
@c    to you.

@c    6:4. And they sent to me according to this word, four times:  and I
@c    answered them after the same manner.

@c    6:5. And Sanaballat sent his servant to me the fifth time according to
@c    the former word, and he had a letter in his hand written in this
@c    manner:

@c    6:6. It is reported amongst the Gentiles, and Gossem hath said it, that
@c    thou and the Jews think to rebel, and therefore thou buildest the wall,
@c    and hast a mind to set thyself king over them:  for which end

@c    6:7. Thou hast also set up prophets, to preach of thee at Jerusalem,
@c    saying:  There is a king in Judea.  The king will hear of these things:
@c    therefore come now, that we may take counsel together.

@c    6:8. And I sent to them, saying:  There is no such thing done as thou
@c    sayest:  but thou feignest these things out of thy own heart.

@c    6:9. For all these men thought to frighten us, thinking that our hands
@c    would cease from the work, and that we would leave off.  Wherefore I
@c    strengthened my hands the more:

@c    6:10. And I went into the house of Samaia the son of Delaia, the son of
@c    Metabeel privately.  And he said:  Let us consult together in the house
@c    of God in the midst of the temple:  and let us shut the doors of the
@c    temple, for they will come to kill thee, and in the night they will
@c    come to slay thee.

@c    6:11. And I said:  Should such a man as I flee?  and who is there that
@c    being as I am, would go into the temple, to save his life?  I will not
@c    go in.

@c    6:12. And I understood that God had not sent him, but that he had
@c    spoken to me as if he had been prophesying, and Tobias, and Sanaballat
@c    had hired him.

@c    6:13. For he had taken money, that I being afraid should do this thing,
@c    and sin, and they might have some evil to upbraid me withal.

@c    6:14. Remember me, O Lord, for Tobias and Sanaballat, according to
@c    their works of this kind:  and Noadias the prophet, and the rest of the
@c    prophets that would have put me in fear.

@c    6:15. But the wall was finished the five and twentieth day of the month
@c    of Elul, in two and fifty days.

@c    6:16. And it came to pass when all our enemies heard of it, that all
@c    nations which were round about us, were afraid, and were cast down
@c    within themselves, for they perceived that this work was the work of
@c    God.

@c    6:17. Moreover in those days many letters were sent by the principal
@c    men of the Jews to Tobias, and from Tobias there came letters to them.

@c    6:18. For there were many in Judea sworn to him, because he was the son
@c    in law of Sechenias the son of Area, and Johanan his son had taken to
@c    wife the daughter of Mosollam the son of Barachias.

@c    6:19. And they praised him also before me, and they related my words to
@c    him:  And Tobias sent letters to put me in fear.



@c    2 Esdras Chapter 7


@c    Nehemias appointeth watchmen in Jerusalem.  The list of those who came
@c    first from Babylon.

@c    7:1. Now after the wall was built, and I had set up the doors, and
@c    numbered the porters and singing men, and Levites:

@c    7:2. I commanded Hanani my brother, and Hananias ruler of the house of
@c    Jerusalem, (for he seemed as a sincere man, and one that feared God
@c    above the rest,)

@c    7:3. And I said to them:  Let not the gates of Jerusalem be opened till
@c    the sun be hot.  And while they were yet standing by the gates were
@c    shut, and barred:  and I set watchmen of the inhabitants of Jerusalem,
@c    every one by their courses, and every man over against his house.

@c    7:4. And the city was very wide and great, and the people few in the
@c    midst thereof, and the houses were not built.

@c    7:5. But God had put in my heart, and I assembled the princes and
