@c    2 Esdras Chapter 8


@c    Esdras readeth the law before the people.  Nehemias comforteth them.
@c    They celebrate the feast of tabernacles.

@c    8:1. And the seventh month came:  and the children of Israel were in
@c    their cities.  And all the people were gathered together as one man to
@c    the street which is before the water gate, and they spoke to Esdras the
@c    scribe, to bring the book of the law of Moses, which the Lord had
@c    commanded to Israel.

@c    8:2. Then Esdras the priest brought the law before the multitude of men
@c    and women, and all those that could understand, in the first day of the
@c    seventh month.

@c    8:3. And he read it plainly in the street that was before the water
@c    gate, from the morning until midday, before the men, and the women, and
@c    all those that could understand:  and the ears of all the people were
@c    attentive to the book.

@c    8:4. And Esdras the scribe stood upon a step of wood, which he had made
@c    to speak upon, and there stood by him Mathathias, and Semeia, and Ania,
@c    and Uria, and Helcia, and Maasia, on his right hand:  and on the left,
@c    Phadaia, Misael, and Melchia, and Hasum, and Hasbadana, Zacharia and
@c    Mosollam.

@c    8:5. And Esdras opened the book before all the people:  for he was above
@c    all the people:  and when he had opened it, all the people stood.

@c    8:6. And Esdras blessed the Lord the great God:  and all the people
@c    answered, Amen, amen:  lifting up their hands:  and they bowed down, and
@c    adored God with their faces to the ground.

@c    8:7. Now Josue, and Bani, and Serebia, Jamin, Accub, Sephtai, Odia,
@c    Maasia, Celtia, Azarias, Jozabed, Hanan, Phalaia, the Levites, made
@c    silence among the people to hear the law:  and the people stood in their
@c    place.

@c    8:8. And they read in the book of the law of God distinctly and plainly
@c    to be understood:  and they understood when it was read.

@c    8:9. And Nehemias (he is Athersatha) and Esdras the priest and scribe,
@c    and the Levites who interpreted to all the people, said:  This is a holy
@c    day to the Lord our God:  do not mourn, nor weep:  for all the people
@c    wept, when they heard the words of the law.

@c    8:10. And he said to them:  Go, eat fat meats, and drink sweet wine, and
@c    send portions to them that have not prepared for themselves:  because it
@c    is the holy day of the Lord, and be not sad:  for the joy of the Lord is
@c    our strength.

@c    8:11. And the Levites stilled all the people, saying:  Hold your peace,
@c    for the day is holy, and be not sorrowful.

@c    8:12. So all the people went to eat and drink, and to send portions,
@c    and to make great mirth:  because they understood the words that he had
@c    taught them.

@c    8:13. And on the second day the chiefs of the families of all the
@c    people, the priests, and the Levites were gathered together to Esdras
@c    the scribe, that he should interpret to them the words of the law.

@c    8:14. And they found written in the law, that the Lord had commanded by
@c    the hand of Moses, that the children of Israel should dwell in
@c    tabernacles, on the feast, in the seventh month:

@c    8:15. And that they should proclaim and publish the word in all their
@c    cities, and in Jerusalem, saying:  Go forth to the mount, and fetch
@c    branches of olive, and branches of beautiful wood, branches of myrtle,
@c    and branches of palm, and branches of thick trees, to make tabernacles,
@c    as it is written.

@c    8:16. And the people went forth, and brought.  And they made themselves
@c    tabernacles every man on the top of his house, and in their courts, and
@c    in the courts of the house of God, and in the street of the water gate,
@c    and in the street of the gate of Ephraim.

@c    8:17. And all the assembly of them that were returned from the
@c    captivity, made tabernacles, and dwelt in tabernacles:  for since the
@c    days of Josue the son of Nun the children of Israel had not done so,
@c    until that day:  and there was exceeding great joy.

@c    8:18. And he read in the book of the law of God day by day, from the
@c    first day till the last, and they kept the solemnity seven days, and in
@c    the eighth day a solemn assembly according to the manner.



@c    2 Esdras Chapter 9


@c    The people repent with fasting and sackcloth.  The Levites confess God's
@c    benefits, and the people's ingratitude:  they pray for them, and make a
@c    covenant with God.

@c    9:1. And in the four and twentieth day of the month the children of
@c    Israel came together with fasting and with sackcloth, and earth upon
@c    them.

@c    9:2. And the seed of the children of Israel separated themselves from
@c    every stranger:  and they stood, and confessed their sins, and the
@c    iniquities of their fathers.

@c    9:3. And they rose up to stand:  and they read in the book of the law of
@c    the Lord their God, four times in the day, and four times they
@c    confessed, and adored the Lord their God.

@c    9:4. And there stood up upon the step of the Levites, Josue, and Bani,
@c    and Cedmihel, Sabania, Bonni, Sarebias, Bani, and Chanani:  and they
@c    cried with a loud voice to the Lord their God.

@c    9:5. And the Levites Josue and Cedmihel, Bonni, Hasebnia, Serebia,
@c    Oduia, Sebnia, and Phathahia, said:  Arise, bless the Lord your God from
@c    eternity to eternity:  and blessed be the high name of thy glory with
@c    all blessing and praise.

@c    9:6. Thou thyself, O Lord alone, thou hast made heaven, and the heaven
@c    of heavens, and all the host thereof:  the earth and all things that are
@c    in it:  the seas and all that are therein:  and thou givest life to all
@c    these things, and the host of heaven adoreth thee.

@c    9:7. Thou O Lord God, art he who chosest Abram, and broughtest him
@c    forth out of the fire of the Chaldeans, and gavest him the name of
@c    Abraham.

@c    The fire of the Chaldeans. . .The city of Ur in Chaldea, the name of
@c    which signifies fire.  Or out of the fire of the tribulations and
@c    temptations, to which he was there exposed.--The ancient Rabbins
@c    understood this literally, affirming that Abram was cast into the fire
@c    by the idolaters, and brought out by a miracle without any hurt.

@c    9:8. And thou didst find his heart faithful before thee:  and thou
@c    madest a covenant with him, to give him the land of the Chanaanite, of
@c    the Hethite, and of the Amorrhite, and of the Pherezite, and of the
@c    Jebusite, and of the Gergezite, to give it to his seed:  and thou hast
@c    fulfilled thy words, because thou art just.

@c    9:9. And thou sawest the affliction of our fathers in Egypt:  and thou
@c    didst hear their cry by the Red Sea.

@c    9:10. And thou shewedst signs and wonders upon Pharao, and upon all his
@c    servants, and upon the people of his land:  for thou knewest that they
@c    dealt proudly against them:  and thou madest thyself a name, as it is at
@c    this day.

@c    9:11. And thou didst divide the sea before them, and they passed
@c    through the midst of the sea on dry land:  but their persecutors thou
@c    threwest into the depth, as a stone into mighty waters.

@c    9:12. And in a pillar of a cloud thou wast their leader by day, and in
@c    a pillar of fire by night, that they might see the way by which they
@c    went.

@c    9:13. Thou camest down also to mount Sinai, and didst speak with them
@c    from heaven, and thou gavest them right judgments, and the law of
@c    truth, ceremonies, and good precepts.

@c    9:14. Thou madest known to them thy holy sabbath, and didst prescribe
@c    to them commandments, and ceremonies, and the law by the hand of Moses
@c    thy servant.

@c    9:15. And thou gavest them bread from heaven in their hunger, and
@c    broughtest forth water for them out of the rock in their thirst, and
@c    thou saidst to them that they should go in, and possess the land, upon
@c    which thou hadst lifted up thy hand to give it them.

@c    9:16. But they and our fathers dealt proudly, and hardened their necks
@c    and hearkened not to thy commandments.

@c    9:17. And they would not hear, and they remembered not thy wonders
@c    which thou hadst done for them.  And they hardened their necks, and gave
@c    the head to return to their bondage, as it were by contention.  But
@c    thou, a forgiving God, gracious, and merciful, longsuffering, and full
@c    of compassion, didst not forsake them.

@c    And gave the head. . .That is, they set their head, or were bent to
@c    return to Egypt.

@c    9:18. Yea when they had made also to themselves a molten calf, and had
@c    said:  This is thy God, that brought thee out of Egypt:  and had
@c    committed great blasphemies:

@c    9:19. Yet thou, in thy many mercies, didst not leave them in the
@c    desert:  the pillar of the cloud departed not from them by day to lead
@c    them in the way, and the pillar of fire by night to shew them the way
@c    by which they should go.

@c    9:20. And thou gavest them thy good Spirit to teach them, and thy manna
@c    thou didst not withhold from their mouth, and thou gavest them water
@c    for their thirst.

@c    9:21. Forty years didst thou feed them in the desert, and nothing was
@c    wanting to them:  their garments did not grow old, and their feet were
@c    not worn.

@c    9:22. And thou gavest them kingdoms, and nations, and didst divide lots
@c    for them:  and they possessed the land of Sehon, and the land of the
@c    king of Hesebon, and the land of Og king of Basan.

@c    9:23. And thou didst multiply their children as the stars of heaven,
@c    and broughtest them to the land concerning which thou hadst said to
@c    their fathers, that they should go in and possess it.

@c    9:24. And the children came and possessed the land, and thou didst
@c    humble before them the inhabitants of the land, the Chanaanites, and
@c    gavest them into their hands, with their kings, and the people of the
@c    land, that they might do with them as it pleased them.

@c    9:25. And they took strong cities and a fat land, and possessed houses
@c    full of all goods:  cisterns made by others, vineyards, and oliveyards,
@c    and fruit trees in abundance:  and they ate, and were filled, and became
@c    fat, and abounded with delight in thy great goodness.

@c    9:26. But they provoked thee to wrath, and departed from thee, and
@c    threw thy law behind their backs:  and they killed thy prophets, who
@c    admonished them earnestly to return to thee:  and they were guilty of
@c    great blasphemies.

@c    9:27. And thou gavest them into the hands of their enemies, and they
@c    afflicted them.  And in the time of their tribulation they cried to
@c    thee, and thou heardest from heaven, and according to the multitude of
@c    thy tender mercies thou gavest them saviours, to save them from the
@c    hands of their enemies.

@c    9:28. But after they had rest, they returned to do evil in thy sight:
@c    and thou leftest them in the hand of their enemies, and they had
@c    dominion over them.  Then they returned, and cried to thee:  and thou
@c    heardest from heaven, and deliveredst them many times in thy mercies.

@c    9:29. And thou didst admonish them to return to thy law.  But they dealt
@c    proudly, and hearkened not to thy commandments, but sinned against thy
@c    judgments, which if a man do, he shall live in them:  and they withdrew
@c    the shoulder, and hardened their neck, and would not hear.

@c    9:30. And thou didst forbear with them for many years, and didst
@c    testify against them by thy spirit by the hand of thy prophets:  and
@c    they heard not, and thou didst deliver them into the hand of the people
@c    of the lands.

@c    9:31. Yet in thy very many mercies thou didst not utterly consume them,
@c    nor forsake them:  because thou art a merciful and gracious God.

@c    9:32. Now therefore our God, great, strong, and terrible, who keepest
@c    covenant and mercy, turn not away from thy face all the labour which
@c    hath come upon us, upon our kings, and our princes, and our priests,
@c    and our prophets, and our fathers, and all the people from the days of
@c    the king of Assur, until this day.

@c    9:33. And thou art just in all things that have come upon us:  because
@c    thou hast done truth, but we have done wickedly.

@c    9:34. Our kings, our princes, our priests, and our fathers have not
@c    kept thy law, and have not minded thy commandments, and thy testimonies
@c    which thou hast testified among them.

@c    9:35. And they have not served thee in their kingdoms, and in thy
@c    manifold goodness, which thou gavest them, and in the large and fat
@c    land, which thou deliveredst before them, nor did they return from
@c    their most wicked devices.

@c    9:36. Behold we ourselves this day are bondmen:  and the land, which
@c    thou gavest our fathers, to eat the bread thereof, and the good things
@c    thereof, and we ourselves are servants in it.

@c    9:37. And the fruits thereof grow up for the kings, whom thou hast set
@c    over us for our sins, and they have dominion over our bodies, and over
@c    our beasts, according to their will, and we are in great tribulation.

@c    9:38. And because of all this we ourselves make a covenant, and write
@c    it, and our princes, our Levites, and our priests sign it.



